{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"748933b3-5d14-4b64-a91a-a03baf27c826","content":"Here's my assessment of the template:\n\n**Not quite ready.** There are a few issues:\n\n### Critical\n- **`Framework` symbol has no `replaces` property** — Users can pick a framework, but the choice won't substitute into any output file (e.g., the `.csproj`'s `<TargetFramework>`). Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` to the symbol.\n\n### Recommended for NuGet\n- **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation/editor support.\n- **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Required for clean upgrades when users update the NuGet package (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n\n### Nice to Have\n- **No `postActions`** — Consider adding a `restore` post-action so `dotnet restore` runs automatically after project creation.\n- **No `preferNameDirectory`** — Set to `true` so `dotnet new mywebapi -n Foo` creates a `Foo/` directory by default.\n\nThe `Framework` symbol issue is the most impactful — without `replaces`, the parameter is silently ignored.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"28af508b-3a5a-40d7-a678-81fb723a572f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine schema requirements.\n\nIssues I can see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but highly recommended for validation and editor support. The standard value is `http://json.schemastore.org/template`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packaging so templates can be grouped/updated properly.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Useful when multiple versions of the same template exist.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Minor, but good practice for project templates.\n\n\n5. **`defaultValue` references `net9.0`** — This is fine as .NET 9 exists.\n\n6. **Missing `sourceName` replacement scope** — `sourceName` is set to `\"MyWebApi\"` which is fine; it will replace occurrences in file contents and names.\n\n7. **No `postActions`** — Not required but often useful (e.g., restore NuGet packages).\n\n8. **The `Framework` symbol** — The symbol is defined but there's no corresponding replacement in the template files (e.g., in a `.csproj` file). The symbol name `Framework` with the choices won't automatically replace anything unless the template files actually reference it.\n\nThe real issue is that the `Framework` parameter needs a `replaces` property to actually swap out values like `net9.0` in the generated files. Without it, the parameter exists but does nothing. For NuGet publishing, the most critical gaps are the missing `$schema`, the non-functional `Framework` symbol, and the absent `groupIdentity` for handling package updates properly.","outputTokens":801,"requestId":"4022:15632C:4E43CF:5AAA9E:69F00639"},"id":"437f7b98-93dd-4f31-9ea2-44add9c6d8d3","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:58:54.420Z","parentId":"24c50102-daaf-46bb-9458-8e50e3ee88c7"}
